      <p>
        Let <m>\A</m> be the (infinite) set of all compound sentences in propositional logic that can be constructed using the sentence variables <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> and the connectives <m>\lnot</m>,
        <m>\land</m>,
        <m>\lor</m> and <m>\rightarrow</m>.
        For <m>a,b \in A</m> we say that
        <m>a\equiv b</m> if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> have the same truth table.

        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that <m>\equiv</m> is an equivalence relation.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              List of as many non-equivalent compound sentences as you can.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              How many different equivalence classes are there?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\mathbf S = \{a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h\}</m>,
        let <m>\mathbf T = \{a,b,c\}</m> and let <m>\A</m> be the set of all (<m>2^8</m>) subsets of <m>\mathbf S</m>.
        For <m>X,Y \in \A</m>,
        we define <m>X R Y</m> if <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> have the same intersection with <m>\mathbf T</m>.
        Determine if <m>R</m> is an equivalence relation and if so,
        describe the equivalence classes.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\A = \{0,1\}^5</m> be the set of 32 different five-tuples of 0s and 1s, that is,
        all sequences <m>(a,b,c,d,e)</m> where <m>a,b,c,d,e\in\{0,1\}</m>.
        For <m>x,y \in \A</m>,
        define <m>x R y</m> to mean that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> have the same number of 1s.
        Show that <m>R</m> is an equivalence relation and write down all the members of each of the different equivalence classes.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>

  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>n</m> is a positive integer and let
        <m>\A = \{0,1\}^n</m> be the set of all <m>n</m><ndash />tuples of 0s and 1s.
        For <m>x,y \in \A</m>,
        again define <m>xR y</m> to mean that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> have the same number of 1s.
        How many different equivalence classes does <m>\A</m> have?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </problem>
</section>

